column36: British debutant whose French form, shown at Auteuil, has substance; interesting
column37: British debutant whose French promise comprised a second-place finish and narrow win, both at Auteuil (1m7f/2m1f, heavy/very soft); the form has substance and he's an interesting contender.

column4: JCB Triumph Trial Juvenile Hurdle (Registered As The Prestbury Juvenile Hurdle) (Grade 2) (GBB Race)
column20: 5/2 Precious Man, 3/1 Parchment, 9/2 Hallelujah U,  Secret Force, 12/1 One Horse Town, 14/1 Galactique,  Kate O'Riley, 20/1 Hopes Are High,  Lord, 25/1 Wolf Rayet, 40/1 Kasper Hauser
column36: Readily success at Clairefontaine in sole French start; potentially useful
column37: Readily justified favouritism in 2m1f hurdle at Clairefontaine (very soft) in sole French start; potentially useful and he's one of two intriguing British debutants in this field.

column4: JCB Triumph Trial Juvenile Hurdle (Registered As The Prestbury Juvenile Hurdle) (Grade 2) (GBB Race)

column27: K Morice,P Mosbeux,Ades Hazan & R Ades
column36: Progressive in juvenile hurdles at Fontwell; new scenario and upped in class
column37: Well held in sole Flat run; record of 211 in juvenile hurdles, all at Fontwell (2m1f, good/good to soft); improving but needs to show he can cope with this different venue and tougher grade.

column4: JCB Triumph Trial Juvenile Hurdle (Registered As The Prestbury Juvenile Hurdle) (Grade 2) (GBB Race)
column20: 5/2 Precious Man, 3/1 Parchment, 9/2 Hallelujah U,  Secret Force, 12/1 One Horse Town, 14/1 Galactique,  Kate O'Riley, 20/1 Hopes Are High,  Lord, 25/1 Wolf Rayet, 40/1 Kasper Hauser
column36: Brings good credentials to this sphere, based on his Flat form and connections
column37: Possibly flattered by peak Flat effort (in 1m6f Group 2 at Royal Ascot) but balance of form still suggests he could make into a useful juvenile hurdler; gelded since last run; connections have landed this prize for the last two years; brings good credentials to debut in this sphere.

column4: JCB Triumph Trial Juvenile Hurdle (Registered As The Prestbury Juvenile Hurdle) (Grade 2) (GBB Race)

column37: Irish 3yo who has form figures of 1312 since joining new yard and switched to hurdles; has work to do to reverse last-time Punchestown placings with Secret Force, however.

column37: Showed some promise with third-place finish, just behind Wolf Rayet, at Chepstow and is open to improvement; however, this looks a very stiff assignment on second start.

column37: Irish challenger; consistent over hurdles and fences for current stable until form dipped markedly in last two outings; doesn't look as if he's about to record a first chase win.

column37: Comfortably justified favouritism at Punchestown (2m7f, good to yielding) returned to fences last time, adding to his summer hurdles win at Galway; open to further improvement in this sphere; respected.

column27: S C E A Pa Ouvry & E A R L Ecurie Des
column36: Had some strong handicap hurdle form and made a smooth transition to chasing at Stratford
column37: Just 1-8 over hurdles but he ran well in some hot handicaps last season, notably when second to Burdett Road in the Greatwood at this meeting; made a smooth transition to chasing when readily beating some seasoned handicappers at Stratford (2m3f, good to soft; handles soft) two weeks ago in a first-time hood, jumping soundly in the main; a smart prospect who commands plenty of respect.

column4: Paddy Power Arkle Challenge Trophy Trial Novices' Chase (Grade 2) (Registered As The November) (GBB)
column20: 11/10 July Flower, 3/1 Be Aware, 5/1 Burdett Road, 13/2 Stencil, 14/1 Brentford Hope, 33/1 Breaking Cover
column36: Five wins since July; ran well in Grade 2 novice last week but faces an even stiffer task
column37: Has made hay since returning in July from a long layoff, his five successes including three 2m chases, and he ran every bit as well as could have been expected when chasing home the hot favourite in the Grade 2 Rising Stars at Wincanton (2m4f, good) last Saturday; however, he faces an even sterner assignment here and soft ground would be a concern.

column4: Paddy Power Arkle Challenge Trophy Trial Novices' Chase (Grade 2) (Registered As The November) (GBB)
column20: 11/10 July Flower, 3/1 Be Aware, 5/1 Burdett Road, 13/2 Stencil, 14/1 Brentford Hope, 33/1 Breaking Cover
column36: Useful hurdler; starts chasing career relatively late and others may have more potential
column37: Useful on Flat and 5-17 over hurdles, his last win coming in handicap at Haydock (1m7f, soft) in March 2024; often highly tried last season, finishing second to Constitution Hill in a Grade 2 here in January; starts his chasing career relatively late and others probably have more potential.

column4: Paddy Power Arkle Challenge Trophy Trial Novices' Chase (Grade 2) (Registered As The November) (GBB)
column20: 11/10 July Flower, 3/1 Be Aware, 5/1 Burdett Road, 13/2 Stencil, 14/1 Brentford Hope, 33/1 Breaking Cover
column36: Classy hurdler, last year's Greatwood winner here; a serious player if taking to fences
column37: Smart 2m hurdler who won the Greatwood at this meeting last year and was second in an eventful Champion Hurdle in March; respectable second of four in Listed event at Kempton on hurdles return; has raced mainly on good/good to soft over jumps but was an impressive winner here on soft; the highest rated of these over hurdles and a serious player if taking to fences.

column4: Paddy Power Arkle Challenge Trophy Trial Novices' Chase (Grade 2) (Registered As The November) (GBB)
column20: 11/10 July Flower, 3/1 Be Aware, 5/1 Burdett Road, 13/2 Stencil, 14/1 Brentford Hope, 33/1 Breaking Cover
column36: Clearcut win on chase debut at Limerick suggests she can take high rank among the novices
column37: Won a Grade 1 bumper in France and made into a useful hurdler last term, finishing fifth in the Mares' Hurdle here in March; jumped well in the main when making a successful chasing debut at Limerick (2m3f, yielding to soft) last month in convincing style; has done most of her racing over further than 2m but is not short of speed; the Limerick win suggests she can take high rank among this season's novice chasers and she's the one to beat today.

column4: Paddy Power Arkle Challenge Trophy Trial Novices' Chase (Grade 2) (Registered As The November) (GBB)
column20: 11/10 July Flower, 3/1 Be Aware, 5/1 Burdett Road, 13/2 Stencil, 14/1 Brentford Hope, 33/1 Breaking Cover
column36: 4yo; promising second over hurdles here in January; gets weight all round on chase debut
column37: 4yo who went off a hot favourite for the Fred Winter at the Festival in March but raced too freely and faded into mid-division; previously shaped promisingly when second in a Grade 2 juvenile hurdle here (2m1f, soft) in January; quickly sent over fences and a fascinating contender in receipt of weight all round.

column4: Paddy Power Gold Cup Handicap Chase (In Memory Of Edward O'Grady) (Premier Handicap) (GBB Race)

column4: Paddy Power Gold Cup Handicap Chase (In Memory Of Edward O'Grady) (Premier Handicap) (GBB Race)
column20: 7/2 Jagwar, 5/1 Vincenzo, 11/2 Il Ridoto, 6/1 Panic Attack, 10/1 Thecompanysergeant,  Coming Up Easy, 12/1 Hoe Joly Smoke, 14/1 Conyers Hill, 16/1 Bad,  Es Perfecto,  Hunter Legend, 20/1 Theatre Native, 25/1 Riskintheground, 33/1 The Other Mozzie, 50/1 Issar d'Airy
column36: Two 2m wins earlier this year but hasn't seen it out on previous attempts at 2m4f here
column37: 6yo who won at Naas (2m, soft) and Ayr (2m, good to soft) earlier this year and could still have more to offer; however, he did not see it out fully in the 2m4f novice handicap at the Festival here in March and performed similarly over this C&D last November, so there's a doubt about his stamina.

column4: Paddy Power Gold Cup Handicap Chase (In Memory Of Edward O'Grady) (Premier Handicap) (GBB Race)
column20: 7/2 Jagwar, 5/1 Vincenzo, 11/2 Il Ridoto, 6/1 Panic Attack, 10/1 Thecompanysergeant,  Coming Up Easy, 12/1 Hoe Joly Smoke, 14/1 Conyers Hill, 16/1 Bad,  Es Perfecto,  Hunter Legend, 20/1 Theatre Native, 25/1 Riskintheground, 33/1 The Other Mozzie, 50/1 Issar d'Airy
column36: Made it 3-3 at Kempton last month; needs to transfer improvement to this different track
column37: French hurdle winner (heavy) who took a long time to get off the mark in Britain but won two chases in a row at Kempton (2m4f, good to soft/good) earlier this year and made it 3-3 there last month (2m2f, good); this 6yo is progressive but needs to transfer his improvement to a very different track.

column4: Paddy Power Gold Cup Handicap Chase (In Memory Of Edward O'Grady) (Premier Handicap) (GBB Race)

column36: Second in the Plate here at the Festival; not in the same form since but not ruled out
column37: He was the only one to threaten Jagwar seriously when under 3l second of 20 in the Plate here (2m4f, good to soft) in March; not in the same form on his last three starts but he's not ruled out now back at Cheltenham; seems versatile ground-wise.

column4: Paddy Power Gold Cup Handicap Chase (In Memory Of Edward O'Grady) (Premier Handicap) (GBB Race)

column36: Three wins this year (including here) but has career-high mark in this hot handicap
column37: Made it two wins in a row when scoring here (2m4f, good) in April and returned from three-month break with intermediate chase win at Newton Abbot (2m5f, good to soft) last month; however, this 8yo has a career-high mark to defy in this hot handicap; best form is on good/good to soft ground.

column4: Paddy Power Gold Cup Handicap Chase (In Memory Of Edward O'Grady) (Premier Handicap) (GBB Race)

column36: Won this 12 months ago and he's just 1lb higher this time around; respected
column37: Made the frame in this race in 2022 (good) and 2023 (soft) before winning it last year (good); failed to kick on subsequently but he reappeared with an encouraging second of four at Chepstow last month and is just 1lb higher than for his authoritative win 12 months ago; respected.

column4: Paddy Power Gold Cup Handicap Chase (In Memory Of Edward O'Grady) (Premier Handicap) (GBB Race)

column37: Heavy-ground maiden hurdle winner who made it 3-3 in handicap chases at Killarney (2m5f, good to yielding) in August; today is a tougher test of his credentials but this 7yo front-runner impressed last time and is in excellent hands to continue to progress; firmly in calculations.

column4: Paddy Power Gold Cup Handicap Chase (In Memory Of Edward O'Grady) (Premier Handicap) (GBB Race)

column36: Progressive novice last season and reappears with his trainer in excellent form
column37: Made it 2-3 over fences when winning at Sandown (1m7f, soft) in January and he improved again when second of 14 in the Greatwood Gold Cup at Newbury (2m4f, soft) in March; this 7yo reappears with his trainer in excellent form and there can be optimism he will continue to progress this term; player.

column4: Paddy Power Gold Cup Handicap Chase (In Memory Of Edward O'Grady) (Premier Handicap) (GBB Race)
column20: 7/2 Jagwar, 5/1 Vincenzo, 11/2 Il Ridoto, 6/1 Panic Attack, 10/1 Thecompanysergeant,  Coming Up Easy, 12/1 Hoe Joly Smoke, 14/1 Conyers Hill, 16/1 Bad,  Es Perfecto,  Hunter Legend, 20/1 Theatre Native, 25/1 Riskintheground, 33/1 The Other Mozzie, 50/1 Issar d'Airy
column36: Easily won mares' novices' handicap here in April but needs to be better than ever today
column37: Heavy-ground maiden hurdle winner who easily won a mares' novices' handicap chase here (2m4f, good) in April when 10lb lower; third of nine at Limerick (2m3f, yielding to soft) last month when back from a break and she could improve for that outing, but she needs to be better than ever today.

column4: Paddy Power Gold Cup Handicap Chase (In Memory Of Edward O'Grady) (Premier Handicap) (GBB Race)
column20: 7/2 Jagwar, 5/1 Vincenzo, 11/2 Il Ridoto, 6/1 Panic Attack, 10/1 Thecompanysergeant,  Coming Up Easy, 12/1 Hoe Joly Smoke, 14/1 Conyers Hill, 16/1 Bad,  Es Perfecto,  Hunter Legend, 20/1 Theatre Native, 25/1 Riskintheground, 33/1 The Other Mozzie, 50/1 Issar d'Airy
column36: Tackled fences just once last season and was an easy winner; interesting contender
column37: Having moved to Dan Skelton she returned from a long absence last season and raced four times, running well in defeat over hurdles on three occasions and winning a mares' handicap chase at Windsor (2m4f, soft) on the other outing; she's 10lb higher than for that win but had bundles in hand and is unexposed over fences; interesting contender on her reappearance.

column4: Paddy Power Gold Cup Handicap Chase (In Memory Of Edward O'Grady) (Premier Handicap) (GBB Race)
column20: 7/2 Jagwar, 5/1 Vincenzo, 11/2 Il Ridoto, 6/1 Panic Attack, 10/1 Thecompanysergeant,  Coming Up Easy, 12/1 Hoe Joly Smoke, 14/1 Conyers Hill, 16/1 Bad,  Es Perfecto,  Hunter Legend, 20/1 Theatre Native, 25/1 Riskintheground, 33/1 The Other Mozzie, 50/1 Issar d'Airy
column36: Kept on for sixth in the 2m Grand Annual here in March; not ruled out each-way
column37: 11l sixth of 20 in the Grand Annual here (2m, good to soft) in March and again kept on well when second at Fairyhouse (2m1f, soft to heavy) in April; travelled well before running out of steam when second on last month's return at Limerick (2m3f, yielding to soft) and it may have been the lack of a recent run that told, rather than a stamina issue; not ruled out each-way.

column4: Paddy Power Gold Cup Handicap Chase (In Memory Of Edward O'Grady) (Premier Handicap) (GBB Race)
column20: 7/2 Jagwar, 5/1 Vincenzo, 11/2 Il Ridoto, 6/1 Panic Attack, 10/1 Thecompanysergeant,  Coming Up Easy, 12/1 Hoe Joly Smoke, 14/1 Conyers Hill, 16/1 Bad,  Es Perfecto,  Hunter Legend, 20/1 Theatre Native, 25/1 Riskintheground, 33/1 The Other Mozzie, 50/1 Issar d'Airy
column36: 5th of 19 at the Festival here in March; goes well fresh; each-way claims on reappearance
column37: 10yo who has run well in defeat in quality handicap chases on his three previous visits to Cheltenham (including on soft ground), most recently fifth of 19 in the Jack Richards for novices at the Festival in March (2m4f, good to soft); goes well fresh and holds each-way claims on his reappearance.

column4: Paddy Power Gold Cup Handicap Chase (In Memory Of Edward O'Grady) (Premier Handicap) (GBB Race)
column20: 7/2 Jagwar, 5/1 Vincenzo, 11/2 Il Ridoto, 6/1 Panic Attack, 10/1 Thecompanysergeant,  Coming Up Easy, 12/1 Hoe Joly Smoke, 14/1 Conyers Hill, 16/1 Bad,  Es Perfecto,  Hunter Legend, 20/1 Theatre Native, 25/1 Riskintheground, 33/1 The Other Mozzie, 50/1 Issar d'Airy
column36: Travelled well when third over 3m1f here on comeback; the drop back in trip is worth a go
column37: Won twice at Sandown (3m, soft/good) during last season's novice campaign and travelled well on his reappearance here (3m1f, good) three weeks ago only to fade into third late on; the drop back in trip is worth a go and he's in with a chance despite Harry Skelton riding stablemate Panic Attack.

column4: Paddy Power Gold Cup Handicap Chase (In Memory Of Edward O'Grady) (Premier Handicap) (GBB Race)
column20: 7/2 Jagwar, 5/1 Vincenzo, 11/2 Il Ridoto, 6/1 Panic Attack, 10/1 Thecompanysergeant,  Coming Up Easy, 12/1 Hoe Joly Smoke, 14/1 Conyers Hill, 16/1 Bad,  Es Perfecto,  Hunter Legend, 20/1 Theatre Native, 25/1 Riskintheground, 33/1 The Other Mozzie, 50/1 Issar d'Airy
column36: This is hotter than he's used to but he's 5-11 over fences and suited by soft/heavy ground
column37: Made it 5-11 over fences with comfortable win in six-runner Class 4 handicap at Bangor (2m4f, soft) in April when last seen; today's company is hotter than he's used to but he's progressive and the recent rain has been a major positive; has won on heavy ground; worth a second look.

column4: Paddy Power Gold Cup Handicap Chase (In Memory Of Edward O'Grady) (Premier Handicap) (GBB Race)
column20: 7/2 Jagwar, 5/1 Vincenzo, 11/2 Il Ridoto, 6/1 Panic Attack, 10/1 Thecompanysergeant,  Coming Up Easy, 12/1 Hoe Joly Smoke, 14/1 Conyers Hill, 16/1 Bad,  Es Perfecto,  Hunter Legend, 20/1 Theatre Native, 25/1 Riskintheground, 33/1 The Other Mozzie, 50/1 Issar d'Airy
column27: S C E A De La Vallee De L'Orne &c Yves
column36: On a handy mark but inconsistent and well beaten on reappearance at Ascot a fortnight ago
column37: He's edged back down to a handy mark and has an each-way shout on the pick of last season's efforts; however, he's inconsistent and needs to improve significantly from his reappearance run at Ascot a fortnight ago.

column4: From The Horses Mouth Podcast Handicap Hurdle (GBB Race)
column20: 15/8 Supremely West, 4/1 Long Draw, 5/1 Kikijo, 8/1 Gowel Road, 9/1 Londonofficecallin, 10/1 Prince Zaltar, 12/1 Priory Park, 20/1 Patriotik,  Good Look Charm, 50/1 Vee Dancer
column36: Dropped right out from final turn over C&D (22-1) three weeks ago; looks vulnerable again
column37: Often front-runner; last eight starts were at Cheltenham, second four consecutive times (including in this race) before Grade 2 win (3m, soft) in January; tailed off in the Grade 1 Stayers' next time and dropped right out from final turn in handicap (22-1) three weeks ago; looks vulnerable again.

column4: From The Horses Mouth Podcast Handicap Hurdle (GBB Race)
column20: 15/8 Supremely West, 4/1 Long Draw, 5/1 Kikijo, 8/1 Gowel Road, 9/1 Londonofficecallin, 10/1 Prince Zaltar, 12/1 Priory Park, 20/1 Patriotik,  Good Look Charm, 50/1 Vee Dancer
column36: Unraced on worse than good to soft in h'caps; otherwise set for another prominent finish
column37: Very good progress last season, winning over 3m on the New course here in December and April; good runs for minor honours at Haydock in May and Cheltenham (just over 2l behind Supremely West) in October on last two starts; unraced on worse than good to soft since going handicapping; otherwise looks set for another prominent finish.

column4: From The Horses Mouth Podcast Handicap Hurdle (GBB Race)
column20: 15/8 Supremely West, 4/1 Long Draw, 5/1 Kikijo, 8/1 Gowel Road, 9/1 Londonofficecallin, 10/1 Prince Zaltar, 12/1 Priory Park, 20/1 Patriotik,  Good Look Charm, 50/1 Vee Dancer
column36: Third of 17 over C&D on yard debut, finishing well from off the pace off 1lb lower
column37: 3-12 over hurdles, with all three wins on soft or heavy (latest last December); good third on last two outings, having left the Newland-Insole stable for £24,000 in between and been given wind surgery; the latest run was in 17-runner contest over C&D, finishing well from off the pace off 1lb lower than today, and he should be primed for a big run in this.

column4: From The Horses Mouth Podcast Handicap Hurdle (GBB Race)
column20: 15/8 Supremely West, 4/1 Long Draw, 5/1 Kikijo, 8/1 Gowel Road, 9/1 Londonofficecallin, 10/1 Prince Zaltar, 12/1 Priory Park, 20/1 Patriotik,  Good Look Charm, 50/1 Vee Dancer
column36: Last two results (Flat) are a concern but runners from this stable demand great respect
column37: Fine strike-rate since June 2023, on Flat and over hurdles, and he stays an extended 2m7f (unraced beyond that as hurdler); had a soft-ground hurdles win in January and scored in both spheres this June/July; last two results (Flat) are a concern but there was an 80-day absence in between and runners from this Irish stable demand great respect.

column4: From The Horses Mouth Podcast Handicap Hurdle (GBB Race)
column20: 15/8 Supremely West, 4/1 Long Draw, 5/1 Kikijo, 8/1 Gowel Road, 9/1 Londonofficecallin, 10/1 Prince Zaltar, 12/1 Priory Park, 20/1 Patriotik,  Good Look Charm, 50/1 Vee Dancer
column27: E A R L Haras De Montaigu
column36: Showing a lot more behind several of these over C&D last time would have been preferable
column37: Effective in the mud; won at Doncaster (3m) in March and best form when third of 17 at Uttoxeter (2m7f, again good to soft) two weeks later; disappointing at Haydock in May, however, and it would have been preferable had he shown a lot more behind several of these over C&D (28-1) three weeks ago.

column4: From The Horses Mouth Podcast Handicap Hurdle (GBB Race)
column20: 15/8 Supremely West, 4/1 Long Draw, 5/1 Kikijo, 8/1 Gowel Road, 9/1 Londonofficecallin, 10/1 Prince Zaltar, 12/1 Priory Park, 20/1 Patriotik,  Good Look Charm, 50/1 Vee Dancer
column27: Mrs M Pallot & Mr J C Pallot
column36: Greater stamina test today should be a big help to this lightly raced 5yo; one to note
column37: Won French 2m1f hurdle race on debut and on chase debut at Newbury (2m4f, soft) in February; he's looked more and more the stayer since with his minor honours over 2m6f and 3m; the latter was back over hurdles at Aintree (good) three weeks ago and a greater stamina test today should be a big help to this lightly raced 5yo; very much one to note.

column4: From The Horses Mouth Podcast Handicap Hurdle (GBB Race)
column20: 15/8 Supremely West, 4/1 Long Draw, 5/1 Kikijo, 8/1 Gowel Road, 9/1 Londonofficecallin, 10/1 Prince Zaltar, 12/1 Priory Park, 20/1 Patriotik,  Good Look Charm, 50/1 Vee Dancer
column36: Creditable 11l sixth of 17 from out of handicap over C&D (7lb claimer); 2lb lower today
column37: Acts on soft/heavy; 3m Irish chase winner in June and scored at Newton Abbot (2m5f) in September on debut for new yard; 11l sixth of 17 from out of the handicap over C&D (under 7lb claimer Harry Atkins) three weeks ago was creditable, and he's effectively 2lb lower today, but he'll need better to win this.

column32: The Isle Of Blue And White

column37: Surged back to peak form when scoring in clearcut style at Sandown (2m4f, heavy) last December; ran badly on her only two starts afterwards and has a little more to prove at 3m, but it's eyecatching that she's won first time out (November/December) in her last two campaigns; now bids to do it for the third season in a row but is 3lb out of the handicap.

column36: Won readily on stable debut at Ballinrobe, then things didn't go his way at Listowel
column37: Came from the back of the field under Eoin Staples to win readily on stable debut at Ballinrobe (2m6f, soft) in September, then finished fifth in a slowly run race at Listowel (3m, yielding) 12 days later when he was caught wide turning for home and those ridden more prominently were favoured; this should be run to suit his hold-up style; one to note.

column4: From The Horses Mouth Podcast Handicap Hurdle (GBB Race)

column32: K P Marsh Plastering & Interiors Ltd
column36: Off 321 days; caution looks advisable, particularly from 8lb out of the handicap
column37: Back from 609 days off with three discouraging runs late in 2024, over hurdles on first occasion; registered a quickfire hat-trick at up to 3m1f over hurdles in December 2021 (plus AW Flat win in February 2023) but caution looks advisable today, particularly from 8lb out of the handicap.

column37: Given wind surgery after a flop in January and has shown progressive form since; ended last term with a second over 3m at Perth and started this one with third of 14 in the Silver Trophy at Chepstow (2m3f, good; acts on soft) five weeks ago on handicap debut; better can still be forthcoming.

column37: Yet to play his hand when falling just after three out in the Silver Trophy at Chepstow on seasonal/handicap debut; followed that with a dominant display in 20-runner handicap here (2m4f, good to soft; acts on soft) 13 days later, leading between the last two flights; up 8lb but highly respected.

column36: Never finished outside first two and won handicap debut last time; shortlisted on return
column37: Has never finished outside the first two in his eight starts under rules, winning five; that includes six-runner race for handicap debut at Newbury (2m, soft) in March when last seen, tongue tied second time; had wind surgery in August; half-brother to Scottish National third Git Maker, which suggests that this step up in trip will hold no fears; one for the shortlist.

column19: It is hard to say who brings the most potential but it might be ROYAL RAMBLER. Second choice is Kap Boy.

column36: Grade 2 and Grade 1 races did not work out; early in career and may yet come good again
column37: Drew 15l clear in Listed mares' race at Haydock (2m3f, heavy) last December on second hurdling start; put in her place when favourite for Sandown Grade 2 (2m4f, soft) in February and pulled up when 22-1 for Aintree Grade 1 (3m, good) in April, but early in career and may yet come good again.

column37: Came home strongly to grab a maiden hurdle at Chepstow (extended 2m3f, soft) in February and built on that when second at Uttoxeter (2m4f, good to soft) in March; had plenty to learn in that first campaign and should retain plenty of potential.

column4: Paddy Power Intermediate Handicap Hurdle
column19: It is hard to say who brings the most potential but it might be ROYAL RAMBLER. Second choice is Kap Boy.

column37: Acts on soft; 2m7f maiden winner with first-time cheekpieces (kept since) in August 2024; best form on last two starts when second from off the pace at Punchestown festival (2m3f) in April and Tipperary (found his stride too late over 2m) six weeks ago, so needs some respect.

column37: Ex-Gavin Cromwell; made a lot of the running for a hard-fought win in maiden at Uttoxeter (2m, good)  and followed up under another prominent ride in novice here (2m4f, good to soft) later in October, both under Freddie Keighley; rallied last time after a bad mistake two out, so could still prove capable of better on this handicap debut.

column36: Comfortable winner of this race (good) last year off 10lb lower; grim results since
column37: Comfortable winner of this race (good) last year off 10lb lower; grim results in his five races since (this autumn's two were on Flat) and there's more to prove on testing ground but, from a yard which also won this prize in 2022, he's not comfortably dismissed.

column4: Paddy Power Intermediate Handicap Hurdle

column37: Trained before this season by Paul Nicholls; 11-8 favourite for nine-runner contest at Perth (2m4f, soft)  last month on handicap debut and had all the answers on the run-in for 7l win; the runner-up won his next start; up 9lb but no shock if he's better than that.

column4: Paddy Power Intermediate Handicap Hurdle
column19: It is hard to say who brings the most potential but it might be ROYAL RAMBLER. Second choice is Kap Boy.

column36: 1-6 over hurdles last season and rather went the wrong way; doing well on the Flat though
column37: First past the post in a Flat race on heavy going; 1-6 over hurdles as a juvenile last season and rather went the wrong way, tailed off in Festival handicap here on final outing; there's little to quibble with in his 2025 Flat record, better than he was last year, including in September after three-month break, so that's the chief positive.

column4: Paddy Power Intermediate Handicap Hurdle

column36: Won Lingfield maiden (2m3f, soft) by 9l in February; badly hampered on return; dark horse
column37: Brother to useful 2m4f-3m4f winner Malina Girl; improved last season and won a Lingfield maiden (2m3f, soft) by 9l in February; next seen for handicap debut here (2m4f, good to soft; 33-1) three weeks ago but any meaningful contribution ended when he was badly hampered at the fifth; dark horse who is capable of better and Harry Cobden is booked.

column32: John T O'Connor & Michael P Gleeson
column36: Heading the right way in Ireland but with more to prove if he's back on soft ground
column37: 2-9 over hurdles in Ireland, the wins in handicaps at Kilbeggan in June and Killarney in August (both 2m4f on good); good third of 16 at Listowel (2m2f) on latest outing; heading the right way but with more to prove if he's back on soft ground.

column37: Sent handicapping in February with wins over the extended 2m3f at Carlisle (good to soft; easing down) and Chepstow (soft; unpenalised) five days later; 20lb higher for this reappearance (3lb out of the handicap) but it's hard to say just how good he might become.

column37: Runner-up to a promising sort at the Punchestown festival (strong form) and easily went one better in a big field at Listowel (again good to yielding) in September; going the right way and tops the list.

column4: Cheltenham Guardians Safeguarding Team Mares' Open National Hunt Flat Race (Listed Race) (GBB Race)

column36: Beat a subsequent winner in an Irish point and has since joined a top stable
column37: By Milan out of an unraced half-sister to winners Davids Charm (smart 2m-2m5f hurdle/chase) and Terry The Fish (useful 2m7f-3m1f hurdle/chase); beat a subsequent winner in an Irish point (soft ground) in March and has since joined a top yard; interesting on rules debut and well worth monitoring in the market.

column4: Cheltenham Guardians Safeguarding Team Mares' Open National Hunt Flat Race (Listed Race) (GBB Race)
column20: 100/30 Eremenko, 4/1 Celestial Tune, 15/2 Amina, 9/1 Rock Sensation, 10/1 Edith Pelham, 12/1 Divine Diva, 14/1 I C U In My Dreams,  Kittys Glance,  Midnight Musical, 16/1 For A Moment,  Katios Queen,  Shotgun Shirley, 25/1 Masked Mistress,  Pollyanna's Dream,  Shinealight, 33/1 Jo's Secret

column37: Changed hands for £180,000 after winning a point last winter and she dug deep to maintain her unbeaten record in a bumper at Aintree (again good to soft) three weeks ago; has a bit to find with some of these on form but also has lots of untapped potential.

column4: Cheltenham Guardians Safeguarding Team Mares' Open National Hunt Flat Race (Listed Race) (GBB Race)
column20: 100/30 Eremenko, 4/1 Celestial Tune, 15/2 Amina, 9/1 Rock Sensation, 10/1 Edith Pelham, 12/1 Divine Diva, 14/1 I C U In My Dreams,  Kittys Glance,  Midnight Musical, 16/1 For A Moment,  Katios Queen,  Shotgun Shirley, 25/1 Masked Mistress,  Pollyanna's Dream,  Shinealight, 33/1 Jo's Secret
column36: Looked useful prospect when readily justifying favouritism at Southwell; obvious candidate
column37: Closely related to the same connections' Doddiethegreat who won the Pertemps Final here in March; looked a useful prospect herself when readily justifying favouritism in eight-runner race at Southwell (good ground) in May; the placed horses haven't done much for that form but the fourth made a winning hurdling debut last month; obvious candidate.

column4: Cheltenham Guardians Safeguarding Team Mares' Open National Hunt Flat Race (Listed Race) (GBB Race)
column20: 100/30 Eremenko, 4/1 Celestial Tune, 15/2 Amina, 9/1 Rock Sensation, 10/1 Edith Pelham, 12/1 Divine Diva, 14/1 I C U In My Dreams,  Kittys Glance,  Midnight Musical, 16/1 For A Moment,  Katios Queen,  Shotgun Shirley, 25/1 Masked Mistress,  Pollyanna's Dream,  Shinealight, 33/1 Jo's Secret
column36: Second of 13 in an Irish point in March, after which she joined Fergal O'Brien for £25,000
column37: Second of 13 in an Irish point in March, after which she joined Fergal O'Brien for £25,000; new trainer does well in bumpers (he sent out the winner of this race in 2021 as well as the second and third 12 months ago) and is also represented by Edith Pelham.

column4: Cheltenham Guardians Safeguarding Team Mares' Open National Hunt Flat Race (Listed Race) (GBB Race)

column21: I C U In My Dreams
column36: Changed hands for £80,000 after running away with an Irish point; respected on rules debut
column37: Related to several useful bumper winners and joined Donald McCain for £80,000 after running away with a good-ground Irish point in May; that form has worked out quite well and she commands respect on her rules debut.

column4: Cheltenham Guardians Safeguarding Team Mares' Open National Hunt Flat Race (Listed Race) (GBB Race)
column20: 100/30 Eremenko, 4/1 Celestial Tune, 15/2 Amina, 9/1 Rock Sensation, 10/1 Edith Pelham, 12/1 Divine Diva, 14/1 I C U In My Dreams,  Kittys Glance,  Midnight Musical, 16/1 For A Moment,  Katios Queen,  Shotgun Shirley, 25/1 Masked Mistress,  Pollyanna's Dream,  Shinealight, 33/1 Jo's Secret
column36: Only seventh of 16 at Fairyhouse in April; rare British runner for her yard in this sphere
column37: Runner-up in a point and a bumper in Ireland but she was rather disappointing when only seventh of 16 at Fairyhouse in April; she's a rare British runner for her stable in this sphere.

column4: Cheltenham Guardians Safeguarding Team Mares' Open National Hunt Flat Race (Listed Race) (GBB Race)
column20: 100/30 Eremenko, 4/1 Celestial Tune, 15/2 Amina, 9/1 Rock Sensation, 10/1 Edith Pelham, 12/1 Divine Diva, 14/1 I C U In My Dreams,  Kittys Glance,  Midnight Musical, 16/1 For A Moment,  Katios Queen,  Shotgun Shirley, 25/1 Masked Mistress,  Pollyanna's Dream,  Shinealight, 33/1 Jo's Secret
column36: Defied market weakness to make a winning start at Fontwell; open to improvement
column37: Defied market weakness to make a winning start in nine-runner race at Fontwell (good to soft) last month, coming from the rear to lead over 1f out; Tristan Durrell keeps the ride; open to improvement and she's one of two plausible contenders for Dan Skelton.

column4: Cheltenham Guardians Safeguarding Team Mares' Open National Hunt Flat Race (Listed Race) (GBB Race)

column36: Well-backed favourite at Huntingdon in March and shaped nicely in third; promising
column37: Well-backed favourite at Huntingdon (good ground) in the spring and she shaped promisingly, losing second only inside the final 1f; no surprise if she steps up quite a bit on that debut form; Alan King trained the dam (2m5f/3m hurdle winner) and has won races with several of her relatives.

column4: Cheltenham Guardians Safeguarding Team Mares' Open National Hunt Flat Race (Listed Race) (GBB Race)

column37: Workmanlike winner under Harry Cobden at Uttoxeter and Plumpton, both on good ground; faces much stronger opposition here and likely to encounter softer ground; others appeal more.

column37: Second in a fast-ground point in May and filled the same position in a bumper at the Galway festival (good ground) in August; related to some useful mud-lovers so these more testing conditions may not cause her a problem; unexposed and merits consideration.

column37: Similar form when placed at Wincanton (good) and Ludlow (good to soft) towards the end of 2024; should be winning races in due course but will need a jolt of improvement to get off the mark here.

column4: Cheltenham Guardians Safeguarding Team Mares' Open National Hunt Flat Race (Listed Race) (GBB Race)

column37: Pulled too hard when a beaten favourite on rules debut, but she settled better and duly improved a chunk when winning ten-runner race at Southwell (good ground) in the spring; should keep progressing and she must be considered for her in-form local stable.

column37: Finished alone in an Irish point in May, after which she changed hands for 30,000euros; hard to assess but she's related to some useful jumpers and probably has a future under rules.

column37: Improved for the fitting of a hood when winning at Uttoxeter (good ground) last month, never far away; comes from a useful family her trainer knows well and further progress seems likely; not ruled out.

column37: Last of four on handicap debut in March and may not have achieved much more when second of five behind short-odds winner in Carlisle maiden (2m1f good) in April; subsequent Flat form was also underwhelming; probably needs improvement.
